'''Prendeur''' is a French term for a laborer working as part of an early [[Middle Age]] share cropping system known as ''complant''-a precursor to the [[métayage]] system. Under this system, the ''prendeur'' would cultivate land owned by a [[bailleur]]. In exchange for using the ''bailleur's'' soil, the ''prendeur'' promised a share of the crop or its revenue. The length of this partnership varied and sometimes would extend over generations. <ref> Hugh Johnson, ''Vintage: The Story of Wine'' pg 116. Simon and Schuster 1989 </ref> 

